Explanation:

I inspected controllers/orderController.js and routes/orderRoutes.js to determine the behavior of the POST /api/orders endpoint. The controller comment and code show:

- Purpose: Create new order (comment: "@desc Create new order", route "POST /api/orders").
- Access: Private (the route uses the protect middleware).
- Request body: the controller reads req.body.orderItems, req.body.shippingAddress, and req.body.paymentMethod. It requires orderItems to be a non-empty array and expects each order item from the client to include at least an _id (used to look up the product in the database).
- Processing: The server replaces client-provided prices with the authoritative product price from the database, constructs dbOrderItems, calculates itemsPrice, taxPrice, shippingPrice, totalPrice, and saves a new Order with fields: orderItems, user, shippingAddress, paymentMethod, itemsPrice, taxPrice, shippingPrice, totalPrice.
- Responses:
  - 201 Created: returns the created order object (createdOrder).
  - 400 Bad Request: thrown when orderItems is empty (message "No order items").
  - 401 Unauthorized: applicable because the route is protected.
  - 500 Internal Server Error: for unhandled server errors.

Based on only the fields and behaviors explicitly present in the provided files, I constructed an OpenAPI 3.1 Operation Object for POST /api/orders. The requestBody schema includes the three fields referenced in the controller (orderItems, shippingAddress, paymentMethod), with orderItems being an array of objects where the controller specifically expects each item to have an _id. The 201 response schema includes the order fields explicitly created in the controller (orderItems, user, shippingAddress, paymentMethod, itemsPrice, taxPrice, shippingPrice, totalPrice). Error responses include simple message objects.

